This past Labor Day weekend, Farah and Porus Pavri drove around town to drop off #AllendaleStrong t-shirts to all who participated in their #AllendaleCircleofSupport (ACOS) fundraiser. This non-profit organization is dedicated to helping both residents in need and local businesses. ACOS funds will be used to purchase gift cards from local shops and given to residents who are struggling financially due to COVID-19. Together they raised $2,000! Thank you, Farah and Porus, for helping to build a more compassionate and stronger community! Their GoFundMe website is: https://www.gofundme.com/f/AllendaleCOS

#GoHighlands #GivingBack #Gratitude

post_text:
Even though Mr. Kubicki could not rehearse and perform with his classes in person for the past few months, he still has been hard at work in our music classes working on auditions, running virtual practices and performances, and keeping music education strong.

We are happy and proud to report that Ryan Yu, a rising senior, has once again successfully auditioned and was awarded a top chair trumpet spot in the #AllNationalHonorsEnsemble TWO YEARS IN A ROW (last year 1st, this year 2nd)! This means he remains one of the best trumpet players in the entire country!

This is a rare opportunity for any student at any school, but for a student to be accepted in both the Concert Band and Orchestra as a top chair is an extremely rare occurrence!

The only way one can audition for this group is if one is accepted into County Band, Region Band, and All State Band or Orchestra, which Ryan was. Ryan will perform with the #NationalConcertBand in Orlando, Florida.

Congratulations, Ryan, and thank you for all of your support of our students, Mr. Kubicki!

#MusicEducation #HSBand #Virtuoso

While Friday was the last day for students, today was the last day for our teachers. Normally on this day, we all celebrate at our annual NH brunch where we would recognize members of our staff. This year, we honored several staff members who are retiring:

Bob Merrilees - 18 years

We want to thank these incredible educators for all of their years of commitment and dedication. These teachers have shown such love to our students over the years. post_text:
Coronavirus is a global conversation, but how are artists responding? That is the essential question the art department asked their students to explore. Student artists were encouraged to respond visually to this historical pandemic. The result is an impressive range of artwork that captures the enormity of their experiences. This video serves as a testament to what our students have endured over the past few months. Matisse once said that, "creativity takes courage," and our talented students have shown just that in their responses to this challenge. These images indicate that teenagers have the strength to persevere and prevail over circumstances beyond their control. We thank Ms. Melle, Mrs. Lardiere, and Mrs. Albano for giving their students this powerful platform to express themselves.

#CovidArt #ArtAsExperience #HighlandsStrong

https://youtu.be/4rkTUhvgqqE

Are you interested in exploring a career as an electrician and taking courses toward certification? Through a unique program hosted by #NECA and #IBEW, the #InterimCredentials program allows HS students to take five courses completely online, which would fulfill the first year of an electrical apprenticeship. IBEW has funded this program and covers most of the cost. In this program, students learn about DC Theory, Blueprints, Codes and Safety, and Job Opportunities. Job prospects in this field are growing exponentially and salaries are strong. If interested, please contact Ms. Hayes in The Career & Academic Pathways program!

#GamifyingCurriculum #EmpoweringtheTrades #SchooltoWork

https://youtu.be/_sDCQ5B-E7M

post_text:
Mr. Meizys conducted a virtual field trip today for his AP Government and Criminal Law classes to speak with Alexander Shalom, Senior Supervising Attorney and Director of Supreme Court Advocacy at the ACLU-NJ. Mr. Shalom has argued over 50 cases before the NJ Supreme Court. In Criminal Law, the students read Michelle Alexander's "The New Jim Crow" and focused on criminal justice reform. The culminating end-of-the-year essay topic for that class is as follows: Are you more likely to be treated more fairly in the American justice system on the basis of race or class? Students were able to engage with Mr. Shalom on various issues.

Thank you, Mr. Meizys, and his wife, Ana Maria Meizys, Esq., for organizing such a meaningful class for our students interested in government, politics, and law. #VirtualFieldTrip #CareerExploration #ExperientialLearning

post_text:
Yesterday, Mr. Carbone and his #DECA Leadership students participated in our school's first #VirtualFieldTrip to an Investor Conference conducted by the #PiperSandersInvestmentBank.
The audience for the conference included CEOs, investors, and members of the financial press.

Twice a year, Piper surveys thousands of teens across the country to understand their buying habits, interests, and fashion trends. As you probably know, teens represent a powerful marketing segment, and what they do/like/play/eat/watch can influence a company's stock price and business strategy.

This week, Piper Sanders released its Spring 2020 Teen Spending Report, and our NH panel served to inform the survey. Highlands has been the only school to participate in this annual panel, and this is the first time it is being done via a Zoom conference rather than at Piper Sanders' annual investors conference.

Thank you, Mr. Carbone, for all you do, and for keeping our students engaged even during these challenging times!

#AlwaysLearning #GoHighlands #FutureInvestors

post_text:
Please join us in taking a moment to thank our Technology Team for their extraordinary efforts, which have enabled our District to keep running on so many levels: District Technology Administrator, Mr. Jose Madhavasseril; Mr. Paul Emporelis, District Network Manager; and District Technicians, Mr. John McAdams and Mr. Chris Djurin!

The Technology Team has been meeting every morning to discuss issues and share troubleshooting tips and fixes. Throughout the day, they answer student, parent, and teacher requests through an open channel via web conferencing and email. As issues become more detailed, they are leveraging Google Meet and Google Hangouts to further diagnose problems. Additionally, they play an integral part in enabling our #NHTVStudios to continue its programming.

Our Technology Team truly has put the "virtual" in our virtual instruction. We would not be able to serve our school community without all of their tireless efforts, many of which are behind the scenes. Thank you for all you do! #NHTechTeam #VirtualInstruction #OneHighlands

post_text: Mr. Mugno and his #HonorsArchitecture students invited seven area architects and engineers to their class to preview and assess student house portfolios. Some of the invited guests included Highlands Alumni taught by Mr. Mugno over his 28 years at Northern Highlands! The students' final capstone projects will be reviewed by these same architects and others on June 4 in the main lobby. This showcase will be open to all members of the Highlands community. Students appreciated this great learning experience and enjoyed speaking with these professionals who offered real-world guidance on colleges and the application process for such schools as Penn State, Cooper Union, RISD, Rutgers, and Maryland. Thank you, Mr. Mugno, for all you do!

post_text:
Mr. Mugno's CAD 2 students recently had an opportunity to tour the Triangle Manufacturing Company, Inc. facilities in Upper Saddle River to see the manufacturing process in action. Students were led by a group of Triangle ambassadors onto the shop floors where they witnessed Triangle’s state-of-the-art machinery in real time. Afterward, the group convened for a presentation by a Triangle engineer, where he showed an array of implants, devices, and components for the students to examine and hold in their hands.

Triangle has had a relationship with Northern Highlands for more than 27 years, where President Dax Strohmeyer was a NH student and star athlete. There are numerous Triangle associates who are Northern Highlands graduates, many of whom learned about Triangle Manufacturing years ago when they were on a student tour. We want to thank Mr. Mugno and Triangle for providing this opportunity for our students! #STEM #BiomedicalEngineering #WorkplaceReadiness

post_text: More #LeoClub news! Members of the Northern Highlands Leo Club participated in the annual Leo Night, hosted by the Saddle River Valley Lions Club. Students spent time collaborating with the Leo Clubs of #MahwahHighSchool and #CavalliniMiddleSchool about ideas for future service projects. Everyone in attendance was inspired by a shared passion for service!

post_text: This weekend, the Leo Clubs from both Northern Highlands High School and Mahwah High School joined together at #ArcherUnitedMethodistChurch in Allendale for a #SoleHope shoe-making party. Our Leos processed over 75 shoe kits made from donated jeans. These kits are then sent to NC for the soles to be added from recycled tires. Sole Hope employs about 25 full-time Ugandan men and women who handcraft the final shoes, and they currently make about 20,000 pairs of shoes per year. While the shoes are handcrafted in Uganda, they started their journey with our Leos! Thank you for giving back! Saddle River Valley Lions Club #Gratitude #ServiceLearning

post_text: In Mrs.Rabadan’s Adult and Adolescent Health Psychology class, students have been working on creating #SocialAction projects, which included raising money for students in need to receive brand new gym equipment. To raise funds, students hosted two cycle classes for students in the NH Fitness Center and raffled off a gift card. Additionally, due to a generous donation from CKO Kickboxing Allendale, students were able to donate to three different schools across the country. Specifically, the money will go to William W. Niles Middle School #MSX118 in the Bronx to receive equipment like soccer balls and basketballs, Cryar Intermediate, Conroe ISD in Texas to obtain items like jump ropes and footballs, and Aexander Stoddard Elementry School #StoddardSchool in California to purchase specially adapted PE equipment like activity scarves and a rainbow parachute for special needs students. Overall, this project will impact 435 kids! #GoHighlands

post_text: The 2020 Governor’s Educator of the Year Program recognizes educators who exhibit outstanding performance in the classroom or school. As you are aware, our selection committee, comprised of representatives from our administration, supervisors, staff, students, Northern Highlands Education Association, and Northern Highlands Home & School Association - HASA convened to review nominations submitted by our staff, students, and parents. Based on criteria set by the #NJDOE, I am pleased to announce that Mr. John Kuzian of our Social Studies Department is the recipient of this award. Congratulations to John for receiving this honor. Mr. Kuzian’s knowledge in his subject area, caring commitment to our students, and dedication to the Northern Highlands school community are truly remarkable. Mr. Kuzian now has the opportunity to apply for the Governor’s County Teacher of the Year!

post_text:
It has been a long-standing tradition for Business Ed teacher, Mr. Bob Merrilees and his son to attend the Army-Navy football game. Once again, Mr. Merrilees kept the tradition alive by gathering our Northern Highlands graduates who are attending the United States Naval Academy at Annapolis and West Point - The U.S. Military Academy

In the 120th game played between these two academies, the Navy Midshipmen broke a three-game losing streak by defeating the Black Knights, 31-7. Navy now leads the series 61-52-7.

We thank the following Highlanders who are serving our country: (from left to right) Mike Nasta '16, Jack Higgins '16, Patrick Shea '17, Greg Coleman '17, and Shane Sosinsky '17. We are extremely proud of who they are and what they are doing! #GoHighlands

post_text: Madame King's AP French and Honors French IV classes visited The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York and Madeleine's Petit Paris to experience French culture and cuisine. At the Met, students explored the Pursuit of Fashion: The Sandy Schreier Collection exhibition and the French Impressionists wing. Students then embarked on a scavenger hunt based on clues in French to find works like The Thinker by Auguste Rodin, The Manneporte (Étretat) by Claude Monet, and La Orana Maria by Paul Gauguin, among others in the gallery. After completing the scavenger hunt, students wrote a paragraph in French about what their favorite piece was and why they liked it. They were then given free time to explore the museum and visit the gift shop. Following the Met, they went to Madeleine’s Petit Paris to enjoy a traditional French meal, where they were given the opportunity to order their meals in French. Overall, the field trip was a great way to learn more about French culture and art and to practice speaking the language! #CulturalExplorations #ExperientialLearning

Contact Kelli at HASAholidayraffle@gmail.com with any questions or to arrange pickup of a donation.

Please come out and support! #GoHighlands #NH_Athletics #NHSportsAssoc

Our Students Against Destructive Decisions Club is running its awesome "Positivity" campaign this Thanksgiving Season and we hope you will participate!

Please take this opportunity to get in the holiday spirit and write a nice quick note/message to a student, teacher or anyone at Highlands! These notes will be printed onto short memo forms and delivered in homeroom to the person during the week of Thanksgiving. Feel free to write one, two, or twenty by just reopening the form and entering a new set of information. If you don't know the person's homeroom, it's okay, because we can look them up!

Please be sure to keep the notes appropriate! (They will be screened and may be removed if deemed inappropriate.)

Thank you for your anticipated participation and we hope you enjoy an attitude of gratitude next week! Please submit your forms by Monday at 2:45 PM!

#WeAreNHEA #SADD #Positivity #BuildingConnections #EnhancingTheStudentExperience
https://forms.gle/1k33DaY2apgs8SbM6

shared_text:
Northern Highlands Regional High School Sports Association
November 19, 2019 at 11:55 PM ·

Northern Highlands Football Team will be playing Woodbridge HS this Friday 11/22/19 at 615pm for the NJSIAA state sectional championship. The last time NH won this championship game was in 1978 – 41 years ago. Go Highlands! The theme for the game is a Gray Out – everyone wear Gray. If you don’t have gray make sure to wear Red and Black!

Admission for the game:

Adults: $4

Students: $3

Checks, Credit Cards and Dollar bills larger than $20 will not be accepted. PLEASE BRING EXACT CHANGE. We expect a large crowd and lines. All tickets will be sold at the ticket booth. Students may purchase advance sale tickets (adult and student tickets) in the athletic office 1130am Wednesday thru 1230pm Friday.

Please note that large bags and outside beverage containers are not permitted inside the stadium gates. All bags are subject to search.

Thank you – we hope to see you at the game – Go Highlands!

Northern Highlands Football Team will be playing Woodbridge HS this Friday 11/22/19 at 615pm for the NJSIAA state sectional championship. The last time NH won this championship game was in 1978 – 41 years ago. Go Highlands! The theme for the game is a Gray Out – everyone wear Gray. If you don’t have gray make sure to wear Red and Black!

Admission for the game:

Adults: $4

Students: $3

Checks, Credit Cards and Dollar bills larger than $20 will not be accepted. PLEASE BRING EXACT CHANGE. We expect a large crowd and lines. All tickets will be sold at the ticket booth. Students may purchase advance sale tickets (adult and student tickets) in the athletic office 1130am Wednesday thru 1230pm Friday.

Please note that large bags and outside beverage containers are not permitted inside the stadium gates. All bags are subject to search.

Thank you – we hope to see you at the game – Go Highlands!

post_text: This past weekend, Mr. Kubicki traveled to Orlando, FL to attend the National Association for Music Education's (#NAfME) National Convention to support junior, Ryan Yu. It gives us great pleasure to inform you that after Ryan took part in a rigorous audition process, he was named 1st Trumpet in the All-National Honor Ensemble Symphony Orchestra. Out of over one million students who audition for their States All-State Ensemble, approximately 500 make it to the All-National Ensemble. This is the first time this has happened in the history of Northern Highlands! Congratulations to Ryan on an absolutely fantastic accomplishment, and we thank Mr. Kubicki for his leadership of all of our student musicians! #GoHighlands #NHMPAA #MusicMatters

post_text: Profesora Azevedo and her Honors III classes conducted an experiment using organic and non-organic apples 🍏 , pears 🍐 and carrots 🥕 ! The current unit of study focuses on how to incorporate a healthy diet in our daily lives. Students had to observe the difference in size, texture, smell, and taste and then report their findings to their group members entirely in Spanish. In almost every period, the results were in favor of the organic foods as their flavor was “sweeter, crunchier and more natural,” as opposed to the non-organic products. One student was able to share in the target language how conducting this experiment made her appreciate the options she has every day to buy and eat healthy foods! Overall, the experiment was a total “éxito” (success)!

post_text:
Feliz Dia de los Muertos!

Mrs. Azevedo and her Spanish classes honored "El Dia de los Muertos," which is traditionally celebrated in Mexico, by creating their very own "calaveritas" (little skulls) commemorating the life of a loved one or pet. Each calaverita has a dedication with an affectionate phrase such "te quiero mucho" (I love you), "te extraño" (I miss you), "siempre te recordaré" (I will always remember you), etc.

May this be a reminder to keep the memory alive of those who have gone before us!

¡Que disfruten las calaveritas! (Enjoy the calaveritas!)

post_text: Northern Highlands earned #BlueStarSchool status for the 2018-2019 school year from #WISE (Working In Support of Education), the organization that administers the #NationalFinancialLiteracy certification test. This national standardized test is administered to students at the end of their personal finance course. Students passing the test earn the WISE Certified Financially Literate designation. Thank you Mr. Carbone, Mr. Merrilees, Ms. DeVoe, and Mr. Sagliocca for preparing our students for the assessment and providing them with a deep understanding of personal finance.

Announcement from the Boomerang Advisors!

Boomerang Project will be hosting our annual community event called C.O.L.L.A.G.E Night (formerly known as Family Night) on Wednesday October 23 at 7:00 p.m.

C.O.L.L.A.G.E. stands for "Community Outreach Linking Learners, Administrators, Guardians, and Educators." The theme of C.O.L.L.A.G.E night is about more than just the freshman transition into high school. Instead, we are going to focus on issues that affect our community as a whole.

We are inviting ALL students to attend and be a part of this important and valuable discussion! Please come and share your thoughts and experiences. If you are considering being a Student Ambassador in the future, this is a great night to be a part of!

#NHBoomerang #StudentLeaders #CommunityOutreach

Last year, two Highlanders, Seohyoung and Chungjune (Ryan) Park, presented a program to the administration with the hope to promote and celebrate #culturaldiversity. Although Seohyoung graduated last year, Chungjune continues to take the lead on this initiative.

On Monday, October 21, 2019 at 7:00 p.m., we are thrilled to have the Korean Orchestra of the Blind perform at Northern Highlands. Despite being blind, the musicians' skills have been recognized by the Korean government and have gained international attention. Last year, this ensemble performed at Carnegie Hall.

That night our three A Cappella groups (Voices, Belles, and Harmonics), as well as our marching band, will also be performing.

This evening promises to be filled with incredible performances and music that will be entertaining and enjoyable for all. We hope you can join us on October 21! 관현맹인전통예술단 Korean Traditional Music Orchestra of the Blind- KTMOB

post_text:
While many students are on vacation, our summer internship program is well underway! Emily Bookstaver and Serena Huang have been working hard at All is Well Boutique in Wyckoff. The All is Well Foundation is dedicated to empowering others, especially those affected by cancer. The funds generated by the boutique are used to support the foundation’s mission. In addition to donating money DIRECTLY to patients in need of aid, the All is Well Foundation supports cancer research and care, local charities and education.

Emily and Serena have organized a fundraiser for All is Well at Circolo Neapolitan Pizza on August 4 from 4-9 (20% of the proceeds will go toward the store’s cause).

Please come out and support this important event! Mention the fundraiser and Circolo will donate some of the profits. #HighlandsGivesBack #EatForACause #CureCancer

post_text: Mr. Brian Dodwell, the Director of Combating Terrorism West Point - The U.S. Military Academy visited Mr. Gornell's US History classes to discuss his work with operational units on key issue areas such as terrorism, counterterrorism, and homeland security. Prior to joining the Combating Terrorism Center, Mr. Dodwell was the Operations Branch Chief at the U.S. Department of Homeland Security National Exercise Division, which assesses interagency counterterrorism strategy and policy at senior levels across the U.S. government. He previously served as a counter-proliferation analyst supporting the Defense Threat Reduction Agency. Thank you, Mr. Gornell, for organizing this event and enriching our students' course experience!

post_text: Northern Highlands Theater Company already is planning our fall and spring productions!
shared_text:
Northern Highlands Theater Company
June 13, 2019 at 7:02 PM ·

Good evening. Mr. Kiely and I are pleased to announce our 2019-2020 season of social commentary. We are excited that both shows offer larger casts and lots of opportunities both on and off the stage for those interested in crew/leadership positions.

Our fall play will be the blistering comedy The Government Inspector, adapted from Nikolai Gogol by contemporary playwright, Jeffrey Hatcher. Show dates, Nov. 14, 15, 16.

Our spring musical will be How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying, the Pulitzer Prize winner for its incisive depiction of the corporate world, by Frank Loesser, Abe Burrows, Jack Weinstock, and Willie Gilbert. Show dates, March 5, 6, 7, 8, 2020.

We will have a brief meeting after school this coming Monday, June 17 (Auditorium) to give you more information about the shows, the auditions, the rehearsal schedules and the opportunities for cast and crew. We will also have information about community service opportunities this summer.

Please forward, pass along, share with friends who might be interested.

Email Mrs. Rokoszak if you have any questions at all!!

post_text:
This past weekend, Northern Highlands hosted our 7th #RelayforLife, and our students raised approximately $70,000! In total, the Northern Highlands community has helped raise over $420,000 for cancer research!

While Relay for Life is a national event, Highlands' event is unique in that it is nearly entirely student run. Most other Relay events have a team of adults who organize the event. Thank you to all of our students who were involved with organizing one of the best run Relay for Life events in our school's history!

We also want to thank Mr. McCabe and Ms. Pierret for helping organize the event, along with our staff volunteers, administrators, and Board of Education members.

American Cancer Society #NationalCancerSurvivorsDay #GoHighlands

post_text: Thank you to Mrs. Ferentz in NH Guidance and her #HighlandsHeroes who visited Brookside School to help 8th grade students prepare for the transition to Northern Highlands! During the visit, our Heroes talked about self-care and ways they de-stress during the school day (e.g., using health apps, calming activities, and a 21-Day Happiness Challenge). They reminded the incoming freshman students to reach out to teachers, counselors, coaches, principal, nurse, and parents when they are struggling or need help. Heroes are here for you! #MentalHealthAwareness #WeAreAllHereForOneAnother #NHClassof2023

post_text: Tonight, at the Bergen County School Boards meeting, two of our board members, Emily Kaufman (SR rep) and Christine Ferrarie (VP), were both awarded the New Board Member Boardsmanship Certification. This award, which can be earned during the first two years of service, requires advanced training in governance and attendance at regional professional development programs, county association meetings, and the #NJSBA Workshop conference. Very few board members in the state are awarded this certification - the first tier of the NJSBA Board Member Academy program. Congratulations and thank you for all you do!

post_text:
The fourth of our eight Honors Model UN groups dispersed its funds today! This group is comprised of 12 students who worked together to raise $5,375.78 of our current total $44,454.40 for the charity #LoveWithoutBoundaries. Students contacted the charity and were paired with Moon. Moon is a 3-year-old-girl from Cambodia and the funds will help with her education, food, and basic supplies. Cambodia has one of the highest rates of violence against women, child prostitution, and human trafficking, so this money will be critical to help her overcome these obstacles. We so proud of this group for finding a worthy cause. The students raised this money by doing the following events:

1. Go Fund Me
2. Highlands Strong Bracelets
3. Tricky Tray at The Drowsy Chaperone
4. "Moon Beads" sales
5. Bake Sale 2/8
6. Bake Sale 5/3
7. Yogybee Raffle
8. Florida Georgia Line Raffle
9. Matthews Diner Donation
10. Jelly Bean Counting Car
11. Acapella Master Class
12. Student Parking Raffle
13. Percentage of CARS at Springfest
14. Springfest Succulent Plant Sale

#GoHighlands! #GivingBack #HMUN

post_text:
Mr. Witkowski's Honors Model UN class is on fire! The third of our eight Honors Model United Nations groups raised $5,309.33.79 of our current total $43,997.40 for the charity #Chance4Children. Students contacted the charity and were paired with Esther, who is a 1-year-old baby from the creche in Kenscoff, a suburb of Port au-Prince. Esther lives with Dieunel and another one of our donor children, Chrisvens. The group was able to Facetime with her multiple times this year and has developed a warm relationship. We are so proud of this group for finding a worthy cause and executing. The students raised this money by doing the following events:

1. Go Fund Me
2. Bake Sale 3/8
3. Tricky Tray at The Drowsy Chaperone
4. Teeth Whitening Raffle
5. Carnivale Donuts Truck during March Madness
6. Springfest Ice Cream Sales
7. CARS during March Madness
8. Bake Sale 4/5
9. Panera percentage night
10. Selling Ritas at March Madness
11. Dunkin' Morning Sale
12. Canning outside of Waldwick Hot Bagels

post_text: Today, the entire student body, faculty, administration, and Board of Education members watched Katie Corren's video entitled "It's Okay Not to Be Okay." The video featured brave students and faculty who shared their own personal struggles with mental health. Thank you, Katie, for your efforts to bring the school community together to shed light on this very important issue. #YouAreNotAlone #MentalHealthAwareness #StigmaFree NH Guidance

Over the past year, Senior Intern Lily Massie has worked with Jimmy Greco, a Grammy Nominated Producer, Songwriter, and Remixer whose credits include Carlos Santana, Miley Cyrus, Beyonce, Britney Spears, Jennifer Lopez, and Train, to learn about the music industry and focus on her singing/songwriting passion. Lily has worked tirelessly to create new songs and videos, and her music is now being played in Chicago, Los Angeles, and Miami! We are so proud of Lily and her devotion to her craft. Way to go, Lily! Lily Massie Soul Azul Music Kyle James Vocals Make-A-Wish New Jersey #AStarIsBorn #GoHighlands
